      "message": "I had a version of this (PS1) that didn\u0027t do inlining in modules (just settings replacement + simplification). That worked, but caused a bunch of blend functions to not have inlined versions of guarded_divide, etc. To keep code-gen as close to current as possible, I had to rework the inliner so that it doesn\u0027t take a program (just a list of elements and some supporting objects). I also had to rip out this assert and the check that prevents operating on builtins. The new world is basically: The inliner is either operating on ALL builtin code, or NO builtin code (though it can be inlining the contents of builtins into non-builtin code).\n\nGiven this - am I right in thinking that we don\u0027t need to wrap builtin symbol tables, if we\u0027re making permanent/shared edits to the builtins?",
